<p>The most rewarding moments online for me is when someone uses my work. In the case of images, to aid this process I&#8217;ve licensed my images as <a href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.5/">liberally as possible</a> with <a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/hendry/">Flickr</a>.</p>

<a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/hendry/189880407/" title="Photo Sharing"><img src="http://static.flickr.com/55/189880407_5e4a8a44ce_m.jpg" width="240" height="180" alt="Bronze age dagger" /></a>

<p>Last week a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Main_Page">Wikipedia</a> <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Special:Contributions&amp;target=Tortfeasor">contributor</a> contacted me about some pictures I took of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Royal_Tombs_of_the_Joseon_Dynasty">King Sejong the Great of Joseon&#8217;s grave.</a> He encouraged me to visit more museums and take more pictures for Wikipedia articles of Korean history featuring the Three kingdoms era. I did just that last weekend and I must say I&#8217;ve never so enthusiastically visited a museum before. Not only did I take a bunch of pictures of various artifacts, I learnt far more than usual and I even took notes. Wow.</p>

